1 PART II. PSYCHOLOGY INTERJURISDICTIONAL COMPACT (PSYPACT)
2 §2371. Psychology Interjurisdictional Compact
3 ARTICLE I. PURPOSE
4 A. States license psychologists in order to protect the public through
5 verification of education, training, and experience and ensure accountability for
6 professional practice.
7 B. This compact is intended to accomplish all of the following:
8 (1) To regulate the day-to-day practice of telepsychology, the provision of
9 psychological services using telecommunication technologies, by psychologists
10 across state boundaries in the performance of their psychological practice as assigned
11 by an appropriate authority.
12 (2) To regulate the temporary in-person, face-to-face practice of psychology
13 by psychologists across state boundaries for thirty days within a calendar year in the
14 performance of their psychological practice as assigned by an appropriate authority.
15 (3) To authorize state psychology regulatory authorities to afford legal
16 recognition, in a manner consistent with the terms of the compact, to psychologists
17 licensed in another state.
18 C. This compact recognizes that states have a vested interest in protecting
19 the public's health and safety through their licensing and regulation of psychologists
20 and that such state regulation will best protect public health and safety.
21 D. This compact does not apply when a psychologist is licensed in both the
22 home and receiving states.
23 E. This compact does not apply to permanent in-person, face-to-face
24 practice; the compact allows for authorization of temporary psychological practice.
25 This compact is designed to achieve all of the following purposes and objectives:
26 (1) Increase public access to professional psychological services by allowing
27 for telepsychological practice across state lines as well as temporary in-person,
28 face-to-face services into a state where the psychologist is not licensed to practice
29 psychology.
